Definition
----------

*biconditional-introduction* is the :ref:`inference-rule<inference_rule_math_concept>`:

.. math::

   \left( \left( \boldsymbol{P} \implies \mathbf{Q} \right), \left( \mathbf{Q} \implies \boldsymbol{P} \right) \right) \vdash \left( \mathbf{Q} \iff P \right)

Where:

   * :math:`\boldsymbol{P} \implies \mathbf{Q}` is a :ref:`formula-statement<formula_statement_math_concept>`
   * :math:`\mathbf{Q} \implies \boldsymbol{P}` is a :ref:`formula-statement<formula_statement_math_concept>`
   * :math:`\boldsymbol{P}` is a propositional :ref:`formula<formula_math_concept>`
   * :math:`\mathbf{Q}` is a propositional :ref:`formula<formula_math_concept>`

In straightforward language, if :math:`\mathbf{Q}` follows from :math:`\boldsymbol{P}` and :math:`\boldsymbol{P}` follows from :math:`\mathbf{Q}`, it follows that :math:`\boldsymbol{P}` is true if and only if :math:`\mathbf{Q}` is true.

